prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our aim is to reach a noise rms of 0.1 mJy for each target in this Science Goal. This will allow a 5sigma detection of the (conservatively) estimated dust mass (see the Table in the Science Justification). The OT Sensitivity Calculator gives a total observing time of 2.33 hours, including calibrations and overheads. This is a detection experiment and we do not have any special requests for the image fidelity.

This is a pure continuum observation and we choose the continuum option for the corelator setup. THe redshifts are photometric and it is therefore not possible to tweak the tuning for possible emission lines.

Based on the optical/NIR sizes of the galaxies on our sample, the typcial angular extents of the dust emission is likely to be 0.3-0.5". None of the galaxies are more extended than 1" (which we use as our LAS). The aim with the observations is not to map the dust distribution, but to measure the total submm emission (redshifted FIR emission). We choose an angular resolution of 0.5" to match our beam to the typical maximum extent of the dust emission.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Two fundamental questions regarding the formation and evolution of galaxies are how they acquire their gas content and how this is turned into stars. Observations at restframe optical wavelengths suggest that at z>4 the gas accretion rate exceeds the star formation rate and the baryonic content is dominated by the interstellar gas. We currently have very limited observational data on the evolution of the gas and the star formation history of galaxies at z>2. It is therefore of vital importance to establish the gas fraction in galaxies as a function of redshift. This is now possible with ALMA and we propose to observe a sample of galaxies at z~2, 3, 4 and 5, using dust continuum as a proxy for the interstellar gas. The sample selection is based on the multi-epoch abundance method which allows us to pick galaxies at different redshifts which are progenitors of a galaxy of fixed stellar mass at z=0. This type of selection is crucial for studying real evolutionary effects across cosmic time. The stellar mass of all galaxies in our sample is high enough to ensure that metallicity will not affect the dust-to-ISM conversion.
